    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-16T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-16T16:00:00-05:00" n="518"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d518">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/357</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-16T22:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 16, 1918, 10 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.35 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>9537. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1"
                        >Sheldon</persName>]:</p>
                <p>No. 434. Your 334.<note n="2" xml:id="d518fn2">Not printed.</note> I have had
                    several interviews with the Foreign Office regarding the terms upon which
                    rations should be granted to Holland. The statement in your telegram above
                    referred to would almost lead us to believe that you contemplate changing the
                    locus of negotiations from London to Washington and the Foreign Office is
                    somewhat disturbed by the report that you had agreed to allow the steamship <hi
                        rend="italic">Java</hi> which was in Savannah and the steamship <hi
                        rend="italic">Juno</hi> in Curaçao, to lift grain rations to Holland without
                    the British <pb facs="0630" n="1464" xml:id="pg_1464"/> Government being at
                    least forewarned that such action was contemplated. I think that unless some new
                    understanding is arrived at the original agreement should remain in force; that
                    the Dutch and Swedish negotiations should be conducted in London and the
                    Norwegian and Danish in Washington. The Foreign Office has cabled Lord <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_RERDI1">Reading</persName> that they presume
                    there is no intention on your part to offer the Dutch their ration imports
                    unless and until the Dutch have resumed negotiations for a general agreement.
                    The British Minister at The Hague reports that the Dutch Government seem to
                    regret the attitude they have taken and that they would gladly find some means
                    without loss of dignity of reopening negotiations. The Dutch Minister here today
                    informed the Foreign Office that he believed it possible shortly to start again
                    these negotiations. If this proves to be the case it would seem unwise, and the
                    British are strongly of this opinion, to grant ration imports except we come to
                    a definite agreement covering the following points: (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)
                    fish agreement; (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) continuation of agricultural
                    agreement; (<hi rend="italic">c</hi>) credit arrangements; (<hi rend="italic"
                        >d</hi>) agreement to supply East Indian products required by Allies. It
                    would undoubtedly facilitate the Dutch reopening negotiations if we should
                    declare that no further boats would be requisitioned. The British, I think, are
                    willing to agree to this as regards those boats which were in neutral ports, but
                    as regards boats that were on the high seas previous to March 20, the British
                    are unable to come to a decision until they examine further how many of such
                    boats might still be requisitioned. The food situation in Holland is doubtless
                    influencing the Dutch Government toward a more conciliatory attitude, and this
                    tendency, if properly handled, ought to be taken advantage of. The newspapers
                    report that export of all foodstuffs to any destination is now prohibited.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
